   "source": [
    "# LLM-as-Judge: Classroom Experiment\n",
    "### Rhetorical Move Classification in Political Speech\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "In this exercise you will:\n",
    "1. Read agent-produced classifications of rhetorical moves in political speech excerpts\n",
    "2. Write your own **judge criteria** in plain English\n",
    "3. Run MLflow's LLM judge against the dataset\n",
    "4. Compare your results with the rest of the class\n",
    "\n",
    "**The central question:** Does the judge apply the same analytical standard to speeches from *different* ideological positions — or does it give some texts an easier ride?\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Rhetorical moves in this dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "| Move | Definition | Example signal phrases |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| **Appeal to fear** | Warns of danger, harm, or catastrophe to motivate action | *'threatens our way of life', 'at risk', 'before it's too late'* |\n",
    "| **Appeal to unity** | Invokes shared identity to suppress disagreement or build coalition | *'we are all in this together', 'real Americans', 'one people'* |\n",
    "| **Appeal to scarcity** | Frames a resource, value, or window of time as running out | *'running out of time', 'now or never', 'what little remains'* |\n",
    "| **Appeal to nostalgia** | Positions a past state as ideal and the present as a decline from it | *'used to be', 'once great', 'what we have lost'* |\n",
    "\n",
    "The agent's job is to: (1) identify which moves are present, (2) quote the relevant phrase, and (3) explain how the move functions in context.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Cell 1 — Install dependencies\n",
    "Run this first. The kernel will restart automatically — that is expected."
